photo.description: One of the smaller architectural gems in Granada is the Corral del Carbón. Dating to the 14th century, this is one of the older Moorish building left in Granada. One enters through an elaborately decorated horseshoe arch, which is an unusual example of exterior decoration (arab buildings tend to focus on interior decoration). The underside of the arch is a wonderful example of muqarnas, where carved or molded geometrical forms are used to create elaborate surface textures which were then often further decorated with, e.g., painting. These tend to catch the light in cools ways, giving a strong sense of depth to their surfaces.

photo.description: This is the only "funduq" (inn) from the Moorish period left intact in all of Spain, and it's been restored quite nicely. It dates from the 14th century, at which point the small Kingdom of Granada was the only vestige of Islamic rule left on the peninsula, managing to cling on until January 1492.
